== Biography == In {{ill|Bunei 11|ja|文永11年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunei 11|qq=}} (1274), during the {{ill|Battle of Bun'ei|ja|文永の役|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Bun'ei|qq=}}, Suketoki made his debut in combat at the age of 12, fighting alongside his uncle, {{ill|Shōni Kagesuke|ja|少弐景資|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōni Kagesuke|qq=}}. During the {{ill|Battle of Kōan|ja|弘安の役|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Kōan|qq=}} in {{ill|Kōan 4|ja|弘安4年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōan 4|qq=}} (1281), he fought alongside his grandfather {{ill|Shōni Sukenaga|ja|少弐資能|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōni Sukenaga|qq=}}, his father, and other family members, leading Japanese forces against the {{ill|Eastern Route Army|ja|東路軍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eastern Route Army|qq=}} occupying Iki Island. He died in battle at the age of 19.
Following the defeat of the Eastern Route Army on Iki Island, the Mongol forces retreated to {{ill|Hirado Island|ja|平戸島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirado Island|qq=}}, and later, Shōni Kagesuke annihilated the Mongol forces at {{ill|Takashima (Nagasaki)|ja|鷹島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takashima (Nagasaki)|qq=}}. In {{ill|Taishō 4|ja|大正4年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō 4|qq=}} (1915), Suketoki was posthumously awarded the Rank of Junior Fourth Rank.
Suketoki is enshrined as a deity at {{ill|Iki Gokoku Shrine|lt=Iki Gokoku Shrine|lt=Iki Shrine|ja|壱岐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iki Shrine|qq=}} and {{ill|Iki Gokoku Shrine|ja|壱岐護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iki Gokoku Shrine|qq=}} in Ashibe Town, Iki City. A stone grave dedicated to him is located in the adjacent Shōni Park, where he is affectionately known as "Shōni-sama."
== Related Historical Sites == * '''Grave of Shōni Suketoki''' (Ashibe Town, Iki City) Located near {{ill|Iki Gokoku Shrine|lt=Iki Gokoku Shrine|lt=Iki Shrine|ja|壱岐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iki Shrine|qq=}}, the grave is part of "Shōni Park," which also includes a monument commemorating the {{ill|Battle of Kōan|ja|弘安の役|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Kōan|qq=}}, anchor stones believed to be from Japanese ships of the period, and a {{ill|smoke signal|ja|狼煙|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/smoke signal|qq=}} station.
